Parliament did not ratify the amendment for Tymosenko's release
The Ukrainian parliament has rejected, as part of an amendment to criminal law, the draft repeal of the paragraph relating to the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the leader of the opposition.
MPs rejected at second reading the draft amendment aimed at reducing sentences for economic offences, which could have opened the doors to freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to 7 years in prison for striking a seemingly disadvantageous deal with Russia to buy natural gas.
The judgement is not final and the court is due to rule on the convict's appeal in December.
Tymosenko calls the ruling a political revenge by the regime and has provoked a process of suspicions of bias from the court also in the west.
The bill to annul paragraph 365 of the Criminal Law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was signed by 147 deputies.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve it.
