IBM History: From slices of cheese to flights into the cosmos.
IBM (International Business Machines) was born in New York a hundred years ago; it initially had the complicated name of Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It changed its name to IBM in 1924 - initially a trademark used by a branch of a firm in Canada and South America.
The basis of the future IBM was the merger of four firms whose history is linked to the 80s of the nineteenth century.
They had technologies such as the old "time clocks", the clocks that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 chaired the company's Supervisory Board.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm Thomas J. Watson to help him run the company.
The leader then overshadowed the founder of the firm - it is on Watson's ideas that the identity and culture of the company rests until now.
Watson became head of the Kusqu firm in 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began with the production of every possible machine for business and commerce - from cheese and meat slicers to cash registers.
In Watson's first four years as director, sales grew to $9 million and began expanding to all parts of the world.
Watson was so irreplaceable to the firm that after 40 years of management his son became director, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership IBM began the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 60s the people and computers at IBM helped NASA guide flights into the cosmos - on Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the flight on the Moon.
Meanwhile in 1964 IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM System/360.
The classic PC that determined the computer standard of the time with the name IBM 5150 arrived on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later IBM sold its computer factory to the Chinese company Lenovo, but bought the consulting company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to deal with consulting and services with high added value.
The strategy that has been successful at IBM over the past three years - is the Smarter Planet concept "a smarter planet".
Its objective is the intelligent use of technology in areas not yet exploited, such as transport and city management.
As for the field of commerce, IBM recently developed a "Smarter Commerce" platform that helps salespeople manage the entire business cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in our territory.
It created its branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932, then the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM RT, there is also the strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central and Eastern Europe headquarters in Prague and there is also the world-class research and development team that deals with speech recognition.
