How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered trips mostly to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the West was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for holidays to East Germany, the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A big exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when it was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia then the regime began to have an inclination towards the west and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for citizens of the socialist bloc (also for Czechoslovaks) to travel individually even within the framework of socialist countries.
In case the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed a letter of invitation otherwise the individual trip was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West however you had to queue all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that it was not yet won.
The currency deal that was the condition for traveling to the west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who couldn't travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency, however, was not exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the agreement of currencies (Western currency) to travel to the West.
Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where there were consequently many country houses and cottages that Czechs bought and this habit continues until now.
Since 1989, the travel of Czechs has undergone a great revolution.
Although until 1989 holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were at their maximum, last year Czechs spent 4 million vacation days abroad in countries around the world.
The great paradox of which we are not aware today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because it was part of the Yugoslavia of the time.
The abolition of visas in the 90s of the last century in the western neighboring countries caused a huge wave of short-term visits especially to Austria, Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not travel by plane to the west for a long time, which everyone wanted to see for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, travel organizations made Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay for hotels or board.
The typical feature of a trip of Czechs at that time was to take with you your own food preserves, sausage, etc. to save.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech koruna which finally allowed our tourists after decades to be able to freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living as well as the average salary have increased, which has provoked around the year 1997 another important moment.
Thanks to a growing demand for travel, travel agencies have started since 1997 to prepare tours with air charter connections that thanks to contracts have tremendously reduced costs compared to what was there before.
At the end of the 90s of the last century the Czechs had visa-free connections with practically most developed countries around the world except the US which later facilitated our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter to an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic was prepared.
Since this year, as every year, direct air charters have taken Czech tourists to distant hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
That's more than 100,000 Czechs who visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolution development arrived in 2008.
On November 17, 2008 the US abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to completely join the group of developed countries.
Also in 2008 Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in history spent more than 15,000 crowns per person on holidays abroad including ancillary expenses. Crowns per person.
