21st house in Vienna
The Pavilion that moved
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
A history of architecture with highs, lows and a Happy Ending: the Austrian pavilion for the world exhibitions in Brussels in 1958 won awards, was a museum in Vienna, remained empty and then fell into ruin.
Now it is open again and serves as an exhibition house.
If one is enthusiastic about modern post-war architecture, for its clear forms, glass sheds, bright and bold looks and new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the pavilion of the Austrian architect Karl Schwanzer for the Brussels World Fair in 1958 is a good and famous example.
The Schwanzer Pavilion once received the "Grand Prix d'Architecture" for its lightweight and suspended steel and glass construction.
The construction is considered to this day as an important step in contemporary architecture.
He made the architects so famous that he also built the Pavilion for the following Austrian World's Fair.
With its legendary BMW four-cylinder house and adjacent bowl-shaped construction in Munich, it finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His pavilion project as a temporary construction had been exhibited after the Universal Exhibition in the Swiss Garden at Vienna's South Station, was transformed, and in 1962 a 20th century museum opened -
But the building was neither physically nor technically suitable for a museum - no walls to hang the artwork, so not a good environment.
However, it was used for just as long, until contemporary art received a new building in Vienna.
Since 2001 the building has been empty and has become increasingly dilapidated.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has transformed the Pavilion, it now bears the name "House of the 21st century" and will in future be used as a museum for contemporary art.
On Tuesday evening the Belvedere Museum opened, to which the house belongs, the first exhibition - a stroke of luck in every way.
The new beginning was led by Agnès Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian gallery Belvédère in 2007.
Husslein-Arco, promoted an art historian to a considerable career among others in her youth as a figure skater, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Salzburg Museum of Modern Art, she particularly carried out the transformation work with politicians and the protection of monuments,  It has secured and operated public and sponsorship funding.
Apart from contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba whose foundation bears the same name have been exhibited, a café and a bookshop are located there, and an office is to be built there.
Strict monitoring, low budget
For the realization Krischanitz was therefore the ideal performer.
Not only because he had sensitively transformed and expanded the secession of Joseph Olbracht and won the competition, but because he had studied at the Technical University of Vienna and that for him the pavilion was "an extremely important place" place where he had seen "practically every weekend" the exhibitions.
He knew the original project, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost its generosity and lightness following its move to Vienna and its change of use.
In the current transformations, there were big problems: the building was "a sinkhole in energy," says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass facades were changed, insulating glass reinforced with fiberglass was installed and the roof replaced with special safety glass.
Thermal bridge joists have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled coatings have been rehabilitated.
Two basements have made room for the new operation, a dim light panel between the house and the road provides lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - it's almost a new construction, but still the light Schwanzer Pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in a rust protection shade of red-brown color.
And the movie theater is even exactly the same as it once was.
And all this under close supervision of the competent authorities for monuments and with a small budget.
"Often materials that were good and cheap had to be found, and that also pleased the office of monument protection," says Krischanitz and he draws attention to a raw floor in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and transformations, the building remained flexible and light.
It would have been difficult with the Pavilion, "which came from Brussels," Krischanitz said recently, a typical "Drop-in-the-City" story.
Such architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants to "awaken the good conscience".
But in this case the House of the 21st century is not in the wrong place, because if it is a stroke of luck of urban construction: around the Swiss Garden stands precisely the newly planned "central station district", with offices and apartments.
And perhaps another stroke of luck will happen: the 21st Century House could benefit from the reinforcement of another Krischanitz construction, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the temporary Berlin art center, and as it is said, she is already negotiating with the city in order to obtain a site in the vicinity of the Swiss Garden.
