Peter Englund's new book offers depth and generosity. Titled "The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War," it begins with a long list of characters that squeezes your heart.
A tip to start: carefully tear up this page and make it your bookmark.
You will get to know these people in detail. In this romantic tale by Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a beacon during those few moments when, like one of his men or women, you will be troubled and desperate in the mists of war.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
Here he wrote an extraordinary book that he describes, accurately, as "a work of anti-history."
It features some well-known names, important treatises, or famous battles; There are hardly any ambassadors or discussions of strategies and materials.
It's not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as a "book describing what it might have looked like." It includes "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods."
"Beauty and Sorrow" sums up the wartime experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women on both sides of the war, from young schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, paramedics and salesmen.
Some will become heroes.
Others prisoners of war. Some will lose limbs, go crazy or lose their lives.
Their lives waver here like candles in a church: while some are extinguished, new ones are rekindled.
Peter Englund's book departs from traditional history books.
It refutes the idea that the First World War can only be summed up by the terrible trench warfare on the Western Front.
"Beauty and Sorrow" skillfully describes other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are under beehives; one spends Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; Tsetse flies are an intractable problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
War invades the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like a hurricane Katrina that reeks of cordite.
When cannon shots ring out in the distance, and you're a stay-at-home mom, do you stay or flee?
Who will come anyway?
Almost no one can understand what happened, or even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, "the lack of facts has been fleshed out by assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and rumours."
"Beauty and Sorrow" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nanny in the Russian army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a young sailor in the German High Seas Fleet.
Their stories are mainly drawn from memoirs, letters and other previously published documents.
The versions of their lives can be terrifying or exciting, but are most preserved thanks to the accumulation of small moments and isolated details.
Most address deprivation and the ability to cope.
Telling the story of a German schoolgirl, Peter Englund writes: "Ersatz, everywhere ersatz."
"Replacement coffee, fake aluminum, imitation rubber, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
He goes on to talk about alternative food in Germany.
He describes "meat made of cooked rice crushed in sheep fat (and finished with a fake wooden bone); tobacco made from dry roots and dried potato skin; wooden shoe soles."
It states that "837 authorized substitute meats are registered in the production of sausages. There are also 511 substitute coffees."
Some stories are about honor and courage.
An American acknowledges his own drive for savagery and says of war: "You feel that after all, this is what men were destined for, rather than sitting in a comfortable armchair, cigarette and whiskey in hand, reading a newspaper or a bestseller, and rather than pretending that such a veneer is synonymous with civilization,  and that there is no barbarian behind your stuffed and studded shirt.
Conversely, a British soldier realizes that he is very likely to die, and that no one will notice or pay attention.
"When you are resigned to sacrificing yourself, you hope to have an audience," he writes.
It is unfortunately rather comparable to "a condemned man strangled in secret".
Other observations concern the decline of an old Europe and new types of terror.
"The conflict is increasingly becoming a story of economic competition," writes Peter Englund, "a war between factories."
He grasps the arrival of what he calls "a new species within the bestiary of the turn of the century: the well-articulated and ideologically convinced mass murderer, in well-tailored clothes, who executes his butchery while sitting behind a counter."
