After this summer's tragedy, researchers want to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy... Log in to Facebook.
"We realised it wasn't that hard to find them," says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report by the DEMOS think tank on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook is full of so much personal information, Bartlett argues, that researchers could simply use the site's advertising tool to find the people they're looking for with scientific accuracy — the way marketers have been doing it for years.
Jamie Bartlett's team discovered that half a million members are fans of far-right groups in Europe. It targeted them with ads, but instead of linking them to a new group or product, the ads invited users to complete a survey. The questions asked concerned their level of education, their attitudes towards violence and their optimism about their own future.
By reaching out to these people through Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – without leaving the office.
"It's a new way of doing research," Bartlett says.
Some of the results are not at all surprising: the online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be men, young and anti-immigration.
But surprisingly, "those who combine online and offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic, and less violent than those who stay behind their computer screens."
The DEMOS study is just one example of how Facebook has become the new must-have tool in the hands of scientists.
Think tanks, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study all topics that affect health issues such as social trends, through "Likes", wall publications and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content per day, the "data supernova" is generating a search explosion, increasing the number of searches whose site name appears in the title by almost 800% compared to the last five years.
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you might not be approaching on the street.
"Before, when you tried to investigate people in the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You had to go to the party, but they would never have allowed you in," Bartlett says.
"Facebook avoids all of that — you have direct access to their information."
Others say the site could offer a way to identify and address health and social issues.
According to a recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison, and colleagues, young students who posted on Facebook about their drunken exploits were significantly more likely to be alcoholics than students who were quiet about it.
Moreno suggests that students' colleagues, such as counselors, could monitor the site and intervene to possibly help a student whose status talked too often about alcohol.
"You can't treat a problem if you don't diagnose it," Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Megan Moreno and director of the Center for Children's Health, Behavior, and Development at the Children's Research Institute in Seattle, says the Washington Post.
"We know how to identify children at risk, and who would otherwise not be recognized."
Facebook also constantly accesses the information of its users.
The site's data team studied statistics about dating status and Valentine's Day, turnout in the 2010 midterm elections, and a national happiness index (thanks to information only available – digital freedom champions have long argued that the site could make its treasure trove of data available to others for research purposes).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not – in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site is allowed to access your information.
But what happens when Facebook users are part of an investigation they haven't even heard of?
While researchers have clear guidelines for how to collect information other than through the Internet, the situation is quite different online.
"I don't think a lot of users have ever thought about a researcher studying their profile," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, based on a 2006 study he conducted by looking at his students' Facebook walls.
"As far as they knew, the exchanges were only seen by their friends."
Then comes the question of methodology.
Even without going through the Internet, there is no guarantee that the subject of a study will be completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know the degree of truth of a profile or on a user's wall.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do in reality are two totally different things," Selwyn said.
That's why, despite his experience as a technology researcher, Neil Selwyn believes that a notepad and pen are still the best tools one can use.
