But what Apple fans may find most revealing in a recently rediscovered Steve Jobs interview, which will air this week as the opening act for a film in major markets, is how well this creative mind understood the processes and workflows of the products.
He was undoubtedly a creator and a dreamer. He identified with a hippie but was also very meticulous and organized, as well as an organizational chart improver – a man who believed that many business leaders suffered from a "disease that makes them think a great idea does 90% of the job... [But] a considerable amount of manual labor separates a great idea from an exceptional product."
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the television series "Triumph of the Nerds". This series traces the birth of the computer, and he sits down for over an hour with Steve Jobs for a long and rare conversation.
At that time, it had been about 10 years since Steve Jobs had to leave Apple. He was already working his new IT company NeXT, aiming for popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of the interview with Cringely is used in Nerds, he states that the main copies have disappeared in transport.
It was only after the death of Steve Jobs that a complete video was found in the director's garage.
This slightly edited video is the basis of the 68-minute film entitled Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which will be released in cinemas next Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Steve Jobs here seems surprisingly enthusiastic about laying out technology philosophies and business strategies.
And incredibly attentive.
On four different points during the interview, the answers come a long time after the questions - between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection, during which Steve Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts, in order to provide an accurate answer.
We also discover moments when Steve Jobs' perfectionism resurfaces, where he seems eager to hear Cringely's questions, nudging him to speed up and move on to questions or topics of greater importance.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod or the iPhone, there is a strangely prescient aspect on Lost Interview. Steve Jobs evaluates what he considers good or bad in other companies and shares his own vision for the future of computing.
It's one thing to read the posthumous evaluations of Steve Jobs' career, but there's something raw and inspiring about the man we see here, the anxious dreamer on the eve of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
He explains them and then implements them immediately.
Here's a quick recap of seven notable sequences from Lost Interview:
On how he learned how to run a business:
"In all these years, I've always asked, 'Why do you do things?' and the answers are always the same: 'Oh, just because you have to do them.'"
No one knows why, no one thinks deeply about things in a company.
That's what I discovered.
Steve Jobs goes on to elaborate on his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
Perplexed as to how costs were recorded - one often starts with a "standard cost" evaluated on sight, then adjusted with a "variation" - he developed an automated factory that guaranteed the accurate calculation of commercial costs.
On the opportunity to play a trick on the Pope:
Steve Jobs tells the story of the "Blue Box" he created with Steve Wozniak - a device that was used to hack telephone networks and make free long-distance calls.
The device has been the subject of much writing beforehand, but Steve Jobs' euphoria here in his description of the Blue Box as an act of appropriation is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a pay phone, making a call and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while bypassing as many satellites as possible.
"We'd wrap the ball in different things half a dozen times and you'd scream into the pay phone and it would happen to you a minute later on the pay phone next door," Jobs laughs.
"We were young and thanks to this Blue Box, we learned that we ourselves could create something that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world."
We didn't know much together, but we were able to invent a little thing that could control big things. It was an incredible lesson, and I don't think Apple would have ever existed without it.
Steve Jobs goes on to recount a wonderful trick that he and Wozniak devised: he phoned the Vatican with the Blue Box in the middle of the night pretending to be Henry Kissinger and asked to speak to the Pope.
While several members of the Catholic hierarchy are summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two accomplices go crazy laughing just before the Pope himself is awakened.
On his love of technology (and Bill Hewlett's canvassing):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to make a frequency meter, he looked for Bill Hewlett's number in the phone book and gave him a call.
Shortly after their 20-minute conversation, Steve Jobs landed a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It had a remarkable influence on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and that shaped my definition of a company and how employees are treated."
Steve Jobs later became one of the HP employees to visit the company's research labs, located in Palo Alto, where he discovered the "first desktop computer ever designed."
It was as big as a suitcase, had a small cathode ray tube. I fell in love with it.
The teenager that I was went back to HP and started writing programs for this machine.
On the improvisation of innovation:
At several points in the interview, Steve Jobs talks about inventing new products on a whim.
Early in his career, when he was setting up to sell a few printed circuit boards, a client asked him to assemble a complete computer.
Working on only 30 days' credit, he had to take care of the assembly as well as the delivery of the finished devices.
Later, at Apple, he remembers the difficulties encountered in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember big arguments... I was yelled at and said it would take me five years [to make a mouse that would cost $300]. I had enough, went out and went to see a designer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could make for $15 that proved incredibly reliable.
On large companies running out of steam:
Long before he revived Apple, Steve Jobs anticipated how many industrial executives would get it wrong and lose control of their market share.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, you make a better copier or printer, what next?"
You have a monopoly on the market, so the business is no more successful.
Sales and marketing can make it evolve, so [these are the types of people] who end up running businesses and product staff are left out of decision-making.
The product genius that led to this monopoly position is completely rotten by people who can't imagine designing a good product versus a bad one – the manual labor required.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its current size. Xerox would have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They snatched defeat from victory.
On innovation as an art form:
"A huge amount of manual work separates a great idea from an exceptional product... As you develop this idea, it changes and grows."
You learn a lot about its subtleties.
There are trade-offs to be made... Some things you can't do, electrons can, glass, robots, factories too.
You have to keep thousands of things in mind (these concepts) by assembling them together.
Finally, decisions are made by personal taste. It's about trying to expose yourself to the best products that men have created, and trying to bring those things to the product you're creating.
Picasso once said that good artists copy and great artists steal.
We are always ashamed to steal great ideas.
That's part of what makes Macintosh exceptional. The people who worked on it were musicians, poets, zoologists, historians, who simply turned out to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If not for computer science, they would have done extraordinary things in another field.
Scalia and Thomas dine with health law opponents as court meets
On the day the Supreme Court meets behind closed doors to consider the issue of political discord over whether opposition to President Obama's health care law will be heard, two of its justices, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were spotted at a dinner sponsored by the law firm that will defend the case in the high court.
The event took place last Thursday, when the nine judges gathered for a conference to discuss petitions for consideration.
One of the cases involved a lawsuit filed by 26 states challenging ambitious health care reform passed by Congress last year, a law that has been a rallying point for conservative activists nationwide.
The judges agreed to hear the complaint, indeed, a monumental argument of 5:30 am is expected next March, and the result will probably be likely to favor the destabilization of the presidential race of 2012, which will be in full swing by the time the decision of the court will be rendered.
The lawyer who will stand in court and argue the rejection of the law will likely be Paul Clement, who served as U.S. solicitor general during the George W. Bush administration.
Clement's law firm, PLLC Bancroft, was one of two dozen firms that helped sponsor the annual dinner of the Federalist Society, a long-standing group dedicated to upholding conservative legal principles.
Another firm that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the trade associations that challenged the law, the National Federation of Independent Business.
Another promoter was pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc, which has a huge financial stake in the outcome of the litigation.
The dinner was held at a Washington hotel hours after the court conference on the case.
Among them was Mitch McConnell, top Republican in the Senate and outspoken opponent of the health law.
The star guests at the dinner? Scalia and Thomas.
This is not new: both judges have been present at the events of the Federalist Society for years.
And there is nothing that goes against the rules of ethics.
In fact, judges are exempt from the code of conduct that governs the actions of federal judges.
If they were, they would no doubt argue by the Canon Code 4C, which states: "A judge may attend fundraisers of law-related and other organizations although the judge may not be a speaker, a guest of honor, or on the program of such an event."
Nevertheless, the mere presence of Scalia and Thomas near two of the law firms in the case, as well as a company with a massive financial interest, was enough to alarm government ethics activists.
"This ethical violation and superb indifference to the code contradicts the statements of several judges that the Court follows the same rules applicable to all other federal judges," said Bob Edgar, president of Common Cause.
"The judges were drinking and dining and at a gala fundraiser with lawyers who have cases pending in court."
Their presence and participation in the fundraising of this event disproves any claim of impartiality, and is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas have shown little regard for critics claiming they too easily mix court affairs with the agenda of groups such as the Federalist Society.
And Thomas' wife, Ginni, is a high-profile conservative activist.
On the other hand, the Conservatives claim that it is Justice Elena Kagan who has an ethical problem, not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan served as solicitor general in the Obama administration when the first objections to the law were brought to the trial court.
Her critics have lobbied for Kagan to recuse herself from hearing the case, saying she has been too invested in defending the law to be impartial.
Kagan gave no indication that she would.
Boeing Records Record $18 Billion Order for Airliners
Emirates is ordering 50 Boeing 777 twin-aisle airliners, with the option to buy 20 more.
Boeing also sells six Boeing Dreamliners to Oman Air, a market estimated at more than a billion dollars.
There is nothing extraordinary about a company receiving an order looking at 50 of its products.
On the other hand, it is quite a matter when the company in question is the aircraft manufacturer Boeing and the amount of these 50 planes reaches the record sum of 18 billion dollars.
Equally incredible is who Boeing received this order from: the Middle East, a growing gold mine of future aircraft orders.
In forecasts released Monday, the Chicago-based airline estimates that Middle Eastern airlines will need 2,520 planes worth a total of $450 billion over the next 20 years.
Over the weekend, Boeing reported on the most expensive commercial aircraft order in its history - 50 Boeing 777 twin-aisle aircraft.
It is the airline Emirates based in Dubai that has placed this pharaonic order.
Boeing announced at the 2011 Dubai Airshow that the airline is also likely to buy 20 more planes, bringing the total order amount to $26 billion.
On the other hand, Boeing said Monday that Oman Air has ordered six Boeing 787-8s, nicknamed Dreamliners, a model that boasts significant fuel savings and amenities for passengers.
The amount of these six devices amounts to more than a billion dollars.
"This is clearly very positive for Boeing," said Morningstar analyst Neal Dihora.
"These customers in particular have immense value."
In the Middle East, oil-producing countries own many of their airlines.
So not only do they have the means to pay for these planes, but a rise in the price of fuel - usually detrimental to airlines because it represents their biggest costs - would not be so harmful to them since the country would make money from the rise in the price of oil.
This is important because these companies will be less likely than others to cancel or postpone aircraft orders when the price of oil rises, Dihora said.
"They have natural risk coverage," he said.
Emirates' order reinforces Boeing's dominance in the wide-body aircraft market and helps curb rival Airbus' attempt to encroach on its A350 aircraft.
Boeing's victory at the airshow comes four months after Airbus announced it would postpone the debut of the largest version of the A350, which competes directly with the Boeing 777-300ER.
Airbus is postponing its beginnings to increase its thrust following the request of its customers to increase its load capacity and autonomy.
Boeing shares rose 1.5% to $67.94.
