ADB urges Asia to help eurozone
The Asian Development Bank has asked India and China to prepare to help the eurozone emerge from the sovereign debt crisis to avoid a long-term decline that would impede the development of the Asian economy.
Rajat Nag, the managing director of the Manila-based ADB, said the world's two fastest-growing economic powers must "do everything in their power" to accelerate the recovery of the currency zone through the International Monetary Fund or direct bilateral agreements.
He advised the BRIC countries (Brazil, Russia, India, China) against looking at Europe's difficulties with an "indifferent eye" and warned that Asian financial support alongside Europe's leaders and resources would help avoid a long-term collapse of the world economy.
"We are all together in this crisis."
"So anyone who can help Europe out of the crisis is useful," he told the Financial Times in an interview at the World Economic Forum in Mumbai.
"Asia can be protected to a certain extent, but it is not immune."
"So if China and India can help, let there be nothing stopping them."
In recent months, the eurozone has been seriously shaken by a sovereign debt crisis.
Recently, the cost of Italian borrowing has skyrocketed dangerously and the prime ministers of Italy and Greece have resigned.
Europe's burgeoning sovereign debt crisis has raised fears that the global economy could slip into recession, and prompted calls from major emerging economies to come together to help the eurozone find a solution.
Nag predicted that the IMF would channel any Asian aid, but he also said that such bilateral assistance - such as buying bonds from the US bailout fund, the European Financial Stability Facility - offered greater negotiating power to Europe's Asian partners.
Anand Sharma, India's Minister of Commerce and Industry, said "India will do everything it can" to help the eurozone as its own economy is now suffering from a decline in exports and a drying up of foreign capital inflows.
"Nobody wants the eurozone to remain unstable and turbulent," he said.
"We have monumental challenges ahead and we need to maintain a high level of growth."
"It's not a choice, it's an imperative, because where would we find work for the tens of millions of our young men and women?"
Others argue that developing economies such as India should not help Europe's rich as they face their own significant economic challenges.
Ashutosh Varshney, a professor at Brown University in the US, said it would be politically very difficult to get Europe to accept aid for India's 1.2 billion people, at least 800,000 of whom live on $2 a day or less.
"One day they will find out that Greeks retire at 50 and go on holiday in the sun and they will have a hard time swallowing it," he said.
Lee Howell, the chairman of the World Economic Forum, also questioned why India's reserves should be used to keep many well-paid Greek civil servants in poorly managed jobs that generate losses, such as in the rail sector.
Nag said the eurozone crisis was likely to cause "significant repercussions" across Asia.
BASD's forecast of 7.5% economic growth in Asia in 2011/2012 now faces "risks of loss" because of the European threat.
He warned that vulnerable emerging markets needed to develop "contingency plans" to protect themselves from an economic downturn and significant capital flight.
Pentagon stern warnings about potential defense cuts
Defense Secretary Leon Panetta ratcheted up the pressure on Congress on Monday, warning that impending automatic budget cuts would undermine national security. It has set off a financial chain reaction from the corridors of the Pentagon to the battlefields of Afghanistan, to the gatherings of civilians.
The Pentagon is already digesting $450 billion in cuts for the next decade, but now fears that an additional $600 or more in cuts is imminent if Congress fails to reach an agreement on spending.
"The impacts of these cuts would be devastating to the department," Panetta said in a letter to Senators John McCain, R-Arizona, and Lindsey Graham, R-South Carolina.
He said Congress' failure to reach a budget deal resulting in so-called sequestration, would result in 23 percent cuts as well as the freezing of many new projects.
"Such a large cut, applied indiscriminately, would render most of our ships and construction projects unenforceable — you can't buy three-quarters of a ship or a building — and seriously undermine other modernization efforts," Panetta wrote to senators.
"We would also be forced to divest ourselves of a number of our civilian personnel and, because the reduction would be imposed so quickly, we would almost certainly have to send civilians on leave without pay in order to achieve the goal."
"These changes would shake the faith of those who support our military and seriously damage our readiness."
The cuts would eventually affect combat troops, Panetta said.
"While wartime funding of overseas contingency accounts would not be directly affected by sequestration, war efforts would be negatively affected by severe disruptions in base budgets," Panetta warned.
"Contractors would be reduced, resulting in delays in contracts and supervision of contracts that support the war."
"Staff managing salaries would be reduced, leading to delays in payments to war suppliers, and legal and political support would be disrupted."
The two senators had written to Panetta 10 days earlier, asking for details on the potential impact of the automatic cuts on the Department of Defense.
"The consequence of sequestration on the Department of Defense would have triggered a rapid decline of the United States as the undisputed world leader of military might."
"We are vehemently opposed to this draconian action," the senators said in a joint statement Monday afternoon when Panetta's letter was released.
"It's not a consequence we can live with, and it's certainly not the one we should impose on ourselves."
"Kidnapping is a threat to U.S. national security interests, and it shouldn't have to happen."
Whether Panetta's letter and recent warnings from senators increase pressure for a budget compromise or a call to exempt the Pentagon from cuts remains to be seen.
Panetta has been increasingly vocal about possible cuts, even though he himself rose to the Pentagon's top job with years of budget expertise in Congress and the White House and knowing he faced tough choices.
At a press conference last week, the defense secretary painted a bleak picture of what could happen — a military man with a shell, but no core.
"It's a ship without sailors."
"It's a brigade without bullets."
"It's a fighter plane, without enough trained pilots."
"It's a paper tiger, an army of barracks, buildings and bombs that don't have enough trained soldiers capable of accomplishing the mission," Panetta said in his opening remarks to the Pentagon.
"It is a depressed force, ill-prepared and unable to deal with potential adversaries."
"De facto, it invites aggression."
In an addendum to his letters to McCain and Graham, Panetta specifically spelled out how further reductions could "generate significant operational risks: response time to crises, conflicts, and disasters; severe limits on our ability to deploy and engage in the world; and unacceptable assumed risk in future combat operations."
And Panetta said some of the biggest defense projects could go to the chopper, including those already tested and some just in the early stages of planning.
That list included the Fighter F35 Joint Strike, a planned new bomber, the next-generation ballistic submarine, the new littoral combat ship and the new field vehicle, which would replace the Army and Navy Humvee.
Halting development and testing of the F35 could generate $80 billion in savings over 10 years, but proponents say it's a critical step in improving and responding to potential threats from China and other rivals.
How to spot a lie
A look at recent headlines indicates how pervasive deception and lies are in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; Each side accusing the other of lying.
Penn State administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly covering up reports that a retired football coach sexually assaulted boys.
Last week French President Nicolas Sarkozy was caught by an open microphone telling US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lying has destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York Congressman and Internet celebrity Anthony Weiner has come across as an idiot by quickly issuing denials contradicted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign finance violations related to covering up an extramarital affair.
And then, none of the people who lived through history will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton unleashed by lying during his second term about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
Stories of cheating on school and university tests are legion.
There have been cases where teachers have given test answers to students in order to make themselves look good on their performance assessments.
Mentors who should teach otherwise send the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we encounter?
On any given day, studies show that you can hear from 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are pious lies.
Another study showed that strangers lie to each other three times in the first 10 minutes of their encounter.
Detecting or spotting lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game like, say, charades, where the goal is to exclaim, "I got you," deception detection is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research into such projects, including psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about lying have been debunked.
Liars look you in the eye.
They don't always stutter, blush, or fidget.
Do not conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to unmask.
A skilled lie detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, facial microexpressions, question formation, and response time.
I have spent several years examining scientific findings in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge about deception, and it is clear that detecting deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful for navigating our complex world – especially if your job responsibilities include hiring,  interviews, negotiation or management.
Good liars are adept at reading others well, putting them at ease, managing their own emotions, and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more "centered on them" lies while women tell more "other-centered" lies – usually to protect someone's feelings – that married people lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but that the lies they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you are perceived as a disbeliever, others will feel less guilty for lying to you.
How can you tell if someone is lying?
First, observe your subject's normal behavior.
This is called "benchmarking".
This helps provide a benchmark for measuring subsequent changes.
Observe your subject's posture, laughter, vocal quality.
You need to know if someone is normally wagging their feet all the time so you don't make unfair accusations when you see them wagging their feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for clues to verbal and nonverbal deceptive behavior.
Think of these clues as red flags, not evidence of deception.
Deceptive people may immobilize the upper body when trying to remember their story, they may point their feet at the door, lean towards an exit, change posture significantly, or present "post-interview" relief – an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change in posture when all the difficult questions have passed.
Interrogators often falsely state that the interview is over just to try to trigger the post-interview reaction.
Also, pay attention to the vocabulary of your subject.
The notorious Scott Peterson slipped by using the past while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search for her.
Deceptive individuals may also use distanced language: "I have not had sex with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "wooden language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... If I remember correctly... to my knowledge."
This makes the response perceptual rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing the skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone's chances of avoiding victimization by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
Controversial pipeline plan will be baffled after U.S. threat of belated approval
Days after the Obama administration threatened to delay approval of a proposed Canada-Gulf of Mexico oil pipeline — angering unions while appeasing environmentalists — the company seeking to build the pipeline says it is ready to redirect the project back on track.
TransCanada said Monday night that it will move the proposed pipeline out of the ecologically sensitive Nebraska Dunes area, and is confident the project will still win approval.
The company announced the decision at a press conference at the Nebraska Capitol.
TransCanada official Alex Pourbax says the company remains confident it will eventually get approval for a pipeline, but with a different route.
