Climate adversity has held back the economy
During the first year of Mario López Valdez's administration, in Sinaloa unemployment and informality increased, foreign investment fell and the economy contracted.
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of Mario López Valdez's Government, self-called change, which generated great expectations regarding the advances of the economy, but given the climatic adversity of the beginning of the year, the increase is not observed, in exchange there is a deterioration in the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February, apart from causing losses of trillions for the agricultural sector, limited the possibilities of the state economy for growth, caused a contraction of economic activity in general by 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, justified mainly by the historic decline of 31.16 percent in agriculture,  which has affected the dynamism of other economic sectors.
According to the frost allocation report issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there was damage of 582 million 835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 percent suffered total damage and the rest 21.07 percent suffered partial damage, the main crops affected were vegetables,  corn and chickpeas.
The decline in economic activity generated, until November, a steady rise in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography the unemployment rate of the State during the first three quarters of the year there was an accelerated increase, since while from January to March 55,053 Sinaloans were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 percent of the Economic Active Population,  In the second quarter the rate became 5.28 percent and from July to September the average continued to rise to 6.19 percent, a rate that represents more than 74 thousand unemployed Sinaloans, an increase compared to the first half of 18,969 people.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economics and Social Sciences of the UAS, the rise in unemployment can be explained indirectly according to the actions carried out by public policy.
"What we are seeing is an increase in unemployment that is due to various factors, among which is the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by the legislation approved in Congress to combat money laundering, because for people who earn dollars illicitly it is not easy that they work to earn them,  that they invest them and use them in something," he says.
Detained migration
López Cervantes pointed out that the rise in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
"The number of people leaving the state to work abroad in the United States has been restricted, firstly because of entry difficulties and secondly because when they enter they already have a lot of difficulty finding work, these people stay here and ask for sources of work, which causes unemployment to rise,"  he said.
Lack of seriousness
The analysis of the Sinaloen labor market is aggravated by considering the high level of lack of seriousness that prevails between working conditions, according to INEGI, the 60.38 per cent of the employed population in this state works there without contributing as a worker to any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and lack of seriousness, another reason for the discrepancy for the state are low wages, the entity has the lowest salaries in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Forecast.
The average monthly income of Sinaloan workers was, until September, 5,352 pesos, well below the national average, which stands at 7,0035 pesos.
FDI contraction
Apart from the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, in 2011 there was the largest reduction in Foreign Direct Investment in the last 10 years, according to the Secretariat of Economy from January to June the State's FDI reached 630,697 dollars, which represents a decrease of 87.74 percent compared to 5 million 143 thousand 312 dollars recorded in the same period of the previous year.
In turn, the Economic Development Secretariat of the State Government records a total investment of 17.280 trillion pesos per year, recorded mainly by companies in the tertiary sector.
Debt
In view of the scenario of economic contraction, in July the State Government requested the approval of a credit of 3 trillion pesos from the public congress for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the aim of reactivating the economy.
Reactions
For representatives of the employers' sector, the first year of Mario López Valdés' government demonstrates a lack of management capacity on the part of the Government.
Miguel Loredo López, President of the National Chamber of Processing Industry, said that in 2011 there was no harmonization of the wills of the different sectors, including the State Government.
"The performance of the economy of Sinaloa during this year has been really very poor, we must work intensively to recover the ground we lost this year, in 2012 we must double our efforts, we had to align the effort of all and especially the good progress already synchronized of this new team of Government, let's hope that next year will be much better",  he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López said that events such as the frosts at the beginning of the year have held back the state's economy and have restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic fluxe is produced by several events, between which frosts, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level e flow in processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we close well below the expectations we had",  Says.
Redefining vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Employers' Confederation of the Mexican Republic of Sinaloa said that we want to channel the state towards productive activities of more dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that we have worked, we think it is necessary to develop a long-term program that redefines the vocation and economic direction of the state, because it is important that we detonate the full potential of Sinaloa's material and human resources," he said.
A lot to do
The President of Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better channels the Government's efforts.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has made efforts to give good results in different areas, in terms of economic development there are some advances, but it is important to develop a long-term program," he said.
He pointed out that the current administration has shown advances in the way public policy is managed.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the Government is more inclusive, what I can say is that we have worked a lot and the Government is aware of the fact that there is still a lot to do," he said.
