The Court validates the "analog cut" in Mexico in 2015
The substitution of analog signals by digital is one of the most important changes that the world has suffered in recent years.
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) has rejected the constitutional controversies that the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies have formulated against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analog cut" from 2021 to 2015, because the eight votes necessary to invalidate it have not been combined.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers when he issued the decree that details the actions to be taken to make the transition to digital terrestrial television a reality.
With this result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic, was dismissed for not having reached the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the decree, and this continues to be in force.
The draft sentence, drawn up by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed the declaration of the decree as unconstitutional, due to the fact that the regulation of radio and television is a competence reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reservation of law.
In favor of the project voted only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero itself.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree and by admitting the complaints, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions provided for by it for the digital transition.
The plenary session of ministers also resolved to reject the complaint made by the Chamber of Deputies, without discussing the project for which Minister Sánchez Cordero is also responsible.
In his speech, the Minister President said that he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the Federal Executive cannot structure through general standards the measures so that the public administration prepares for them.
"I also do not consider that if it did so it would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body," and he recalled that public policy planning in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector is the responsibility of the Federal Executive, whose constitutional mandate is the direction of the State.
The substitution of analogue signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes that the world has suffered in recent years and this translates into better exploitation of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
Postponing change, he argued, would postpone the benefits of digitalization, which involves a public interest decision that not only has a technical dimension, "because it also includes economic, social, political and national security issues."
These issues, he stressed, "require the operation of an entire system established, in accordance with the principle of economic direction of the State, encompasses a group of attributions that the Constitution grants to the faculty of the Executive of the State".
He recalled that a large number of countries from all over the world have already completed the digital transition and they have done it through the Executive, despite the fact that they had very specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, by issuing the contested decree, has invaded in some form the sphere of competence of Congress, because it ensures in the administrative sphere the respect of the laws issued by the Legislature, he assured.
The possibility of a vote-by-vote count is being analysed in Michoacán
According to the data highlighted by PREP, the difference between first and second place in the gubernatorial election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6,0074 total minutes.
The possibility of counting "vote by vote" is a reality with regard to the electoral process this year in Michoacán, where according to the data highlighted by the Program of Preliminary Electoral Results (PREP) the difference between first and second place in the gubernatorial election is only 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to the 879 of the 6 thousand 74 total minutes.
In this sense, the President of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los Ángeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, the past 9 November, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines to harmonize local norms with the federal reform in electoral matters.
It will be recalled that Michoacán did not approve either its Political Constitution or its State Electoral Code or its Law of Electoral Justice, at the same time as the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the end of the legal deadline for this electoral process to enter into force and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication within the time limits provided by the Law of the Official Gazette of the State,  with the argument that he had some objections.
On the same November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the Local Legislative Power and qualified as "invalid and illegal" the vote of the state representative for constitutional reforms, because he does not have the right to "sanction or challenge" them.
Asked about the possibility of "voting by vote", María de los Ángeles Llanderal said that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of IEM it will be possible to carry out partial and total votes counts by the local electoral body.
Thus, the partial counting of votes, one or more electoral packages, it may be that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there are no minutes of the ballot and the countdown in the ballot box file is not at the home of the president of the ballot box; or there are obvious errors or alterations in the minutes.
In addition, the total count of votes received in all ballot boxes of the election may be made when there is an indication that the difference between the candidate who is supposed to win the respective election and the one who obtained the second place in the ballot is equal to or less than one percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is an express petition from the representative of the party and/or coalition that presented the second of the candidates mentioned.
The total counting of the ballot may also be carried out if at the end of the joint count it appears that the difference between the candidate presumed to win and the candidate of the second place is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is the express petition of the representative of the political party whose candidate came second,  In this case, electoral packages that have been the subject of the partial count will be excluded.
It should be mentioned that this is the situation of the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP, the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, even without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
