Italy's new government to be formed on Wednesday
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet tomorrow with Italy's President to present the new government that will face a crisis that has brought the country to the brink of economic disaster.
Prime Minister-designate Mario Monti will meet with Italy's president on Wednesday to present the new government that will face a crisis that has brought Italy to the brink of economic disaster and put the entire Eurozone at risk.
A statement from the presidential palace said Monti, appointed on Sunday, would meet Wednesday with President Giorgio Napolitano to confirm he can form the government.
He is expected to present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it is not clear when the new executive will assume its post.
Monti said he would present to the president the outcome of his conversations with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former EU commissioner told journalists.
Monti did not explicitly say he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome.
The "framework is now well mapped out," he added.
Monti completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, in a shorter time than normal, while Italy battles a political and financial crisis that has pushed its debt costs to levels impossible to sustain.
The new administration led by former EU Commissioner Monti must approve a harsh austerity package demanded by EU leaders to regain the confidence in Italy that had been affected.
Underscoring the pressure on Monti to hurry, market instability put the yield on Italian 10-year BTP bonds above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to be rescued.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of Italian employers Confindustria, told the media after her meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government very much."
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to emerge from this emergency situation.
Monti's chances of success have been boosted considerably by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, which was forced to resign last Saturday by the crisis.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts will have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party, told reporters.
The support of PDL, Italy's largest party, is significant because until now many of its members had opposed the technocratic majority government that Monti formed.
Parliamentary support
Monti's new government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what are likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in its efforts could provoke a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign benches added to the pressure by observing that a bankruptcy of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti on Monday began consultations with political parties, trade unions and employers' groups and youth and women's organizations.
He will finish his tour of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who empowered an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it was clear that Berlusconi would resign, Italian debt costs have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty over the success of the new prime minister.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of €1.9 trillion, would be too much for the current Eurozone's financial defenses.
Monti said his government would have to persist until future elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians would only give it time to implement reforms before bringing forward elections.
Monti has said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the major parties insist it should be formed only by specialists, an indication of their objections to a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources have reported that mutual mistrust and disagreements between parties complicate the attempt to include political figures.
