Quinteto included the country in his tour to celebrate two decades of trajectory
"Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In the exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready to perform one of their best shows next Sunday at National Stadium.
They have waited more than 20 years, but the group assures that for them it will also be a dream come true to perform in this country.
That's what bassist and founding member Jeff Ament said, speaking exclusively with Viva, from Brazil last week.
The band is in the South American wing of its tour celebrating two decades of work and Sunday 20 will make its only stop in Central America.
On this day will be presented on the National Stadium, from 19:30 hours, next to the Los Angeles group The X and the nationals of Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the full transcript of which can be found in La Nación on the Internet.
For his Costa Rican followers, the fact that Pearl Jam will perform in Costa Rica is a dream come true. Are you aware of what your fans are experiencing?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is our second time in South and Central America and so far it has been great.
I spent in Costa Rica only once the holidays; It's such a beautiful country and I think we'll be able to spend a few days there.
So it moves us to bring our music there.
I ask you, because there is a kind of devotion to the band, the fans live with intensity the days before.
What is your message to your most ardent followers?
Thank you for staying by our side all these years.
It took 21 years for us to get to Costa Rica; Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry that so much time had to pass until this concert.
Some people are already saying that his concert is the biggest show of the year.
Does it add a little pressure to your visit.
Some of the bigger shows we've put on in the last 21 years have been in the last couple of weeks.
We offered two gigantic shows in Sao Paolo and we hope that it has put us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We're really looking forward to doing it.
We love this country, we love surfing and the jungle; for both things, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
We have a lot of surfer friends and I have a very good friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves are amazing there.
My friends always went surfing in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, next to Mexico, are great places to surf; That's how we learned it, through people who love surfing.
Seeing the tour, you offered huge shows, with a lot of songs.
What do you have planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we have never performed there, we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to make the best show possible, with a wide variety of songs; We will try to perform two songs from each album and offer our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the directory.
What is the reason for this?
I think it's partly because we have nine records and we can perform more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, that's why it's very difficult to choose which songs to perform each night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven't performed in a very long time, it helps us stay focused and surprises us because it reminds us of why we loved those songs and may have forgotten.
It makes the show more interesting for us and therefore I think it also becomes more interesting for people.
With this tour, you celebrate 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe how much you've achieved?
Yes, absolutely.
First of all, I don't think any of us imagined that we were going to be a great rock band, and the fact that we've done it for over 20 years makes it seem like a dream.
We continue to share our blessings and the fact that we can continue to make music together is very emotional.
We love each other and we love making music.
We are lucky to go to places in the world that we have always wanted to go.
Things couldn't get any better for us.
What does it mean to you to have been a fundamental element in the creation of grunge?
It has always been an honour for us to be part of this group of great groups.
We are very good friends with the folks at Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and is unusual.
From time to time, a group pops up from a city, but it's much stranger when five or ten bands come out of the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we went to a festival with Alice in Chains and we went to Canada with Mudhoney, we saw at Soundgarden on their tour, so we're lucky to still be friends with them all and it's an honor for us to be part of that Seattle sound that popped up.
It's also very strange that a group like yours stays together and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, and only that's a lot longer than a lot of bands normally last.
First, I think we are all lucky to still be alive, and second, we all care about each other.
We are all close friends and thanks to this there are musical boulevards that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We trust each other with each other's music and it couldn't get any better.
Your relationship with the word celebrity has not been easy; However, thanks to your success, you have been able to do what you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we grew, it was easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure we don't spend too much time touring because it's easy to fall into this game of the big multitudes and people who love your music.
If we do not forget that people are there for music, it helps us not to forget that we must respect music and what brought it, without thinking about the fact that we are famous and a rock star, which does not really interest any of us.
How do you remember your other project, Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote some good songs and at first it was great.
We were a band for almost three years and we didn't release a record until Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
