MSS announces protocol to find the obesity gene
Social Insurance is leading an investigation to discover the obesity gene in children and young people; this is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is leading an investigation to discover the obesity gene in the case of children and young people, called the protocol 'Genetics of obesity in children and adolescents' that will allow to have the markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, Miguel Cruz López, head of the Biochemistry Medical Investigation Unit of the Hospital of Specialties of the National Medical Center of the 20th Century, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Investigation and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The investigation invites the population with or without entitlement to present themselves to the participating sports units of the IMSS in Valle de México, where the evidence to minors is carried out every Saturday from 8:00 am.
He pointed out that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Estado de México Poniente) and that from October 8, the activity takes place in the Sports Unit of Nezahualcóyolt (Estado de México Oriente).
After reaching the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Independencia Sports Unit (south of Distrito Federal) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of Distrito Federal).
He explained that the objective of this investigation is to know the components and importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and to identify in Mexican children and young people risk factors to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
As World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on November 14, he mentioned that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between six and 14 years old, with the consent and under the supervision of their parents, for the application of specific questionnaires related to diet.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and their history of family heredity of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that on Saturdays anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure, determination of glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics will be applied to all participants (we seek to identify people associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in just six years there was an increase in obesity for boys and 47 per cent for girls; with regard to overweight, there has also been a dramatic increase," said the IMSS specialist.
He said the rationale for the search for markers is based on the fact that the country's population is different from others in its genetic history.
He informed that on average, Mexicans have a 65 percent Indo-American heredity, a 30 percent European and a five percent African and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity result in the inability to burn the excess energy that one consumes (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the integral evaluation of the children, which makes it possible to detect whether they are overweight or obese.
He says that the presence of dark folds (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicate the likelihood of suffering from metabolic alterations and even pre-diabetes.
The information is managed confidentially, with doctors giving it in writing to parents, who are explained each of the measures and lifestyle changes they need to take to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentary lifestyle, which is the lack of daily physical activity, sitting most of the day in front of the TV and using means of transport instead of walking short distances.
Another cause is the high caloric intake, that is, the greater consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales - meat pie with corn flour wrapped in corn leaves -, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid blackcurrants
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry of UNAM, develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with better yield, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the reports that the pavement were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200 thousand blackcurrants each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of Valle de México, warns Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher of the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, who assured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the asphalt pavement is adequate,  Blackcurrants could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his conference A Technological Opinion on Blackcurrants, organized as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops asphalts modified with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve the yield, and consequently, the formation of blackcurrants.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a collection of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, of almost 180 degrees, behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees C it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day depending on environmental and temperature conditions, warns the chemical engineering specialist.
The QF researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de México in their majority were covered by a flexible pavement, composed of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Between the more superficial layers is the layer of asphalt, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and subsequently compacted.
Each of the small stones that form the layer, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
When vehicles pass through it generating efforts, it allows the forces to spread very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, they would spread better, according to chemical engineering.
On the asphalt layer, he says, we put a last layer called the road surface, made of fine stone, that is, sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of vehicles, it must have more mechanical force than the asphalt layer and provide grip on the street.
As the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the forces, the road surface also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material from which it is made must be cared for.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, as these significantly affect the performance of the asphalt layer.
When the soil gets wet, the water spreads inside the layer and it is difficult for it to come out, which softens all the layers of the pavement and consequently causes blackcurrants.
In the process of blackcurrant formation, he says, the first that spoils is the rolling film and only later is affected the asphalt layer, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be cared for at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National Researchers' System explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for the formation of blackcurrants and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be related to the load of vehicles and guarantee its satisfaction, to avoid the frequent formation of blackcurrants.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still much to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and allow blackcurrants to be repaired easily and without having to use high temperatures.
