So was the work of the person from Cali who identified the corpse of Alfonso Cano.
A typist from Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the death of 'Alfonso Cano'.
The work of these officials is crucial.
On November 4, a typist of the CTI of Cali went down in history as the person who confirmed the identity of the supreme leader of the FARC: "Alfonso Cano", by confronting his fingerprints.
Of the seven typists who work in the local offices of the CTI, this week it was the turn of "availability" of Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has worked for 21 years in the field of judicial investigation.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in the municipalities of Chocó, where many times he had to spend more than five days in the forest to get to the place where the corpses that were to be identified were located.
In the year 2000 he was transferred to the capital of Valle and after attending adequate courses, he specialized in dactyloscopy, which is the study of friction skin, that is to say the palms and feet.
During the week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano Eliazar had been warned to take clothes with him for at least three days.
Something very big was waiting for him.
Friday night he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he had to identify two corpses and that it was suspected that one of them was that of the man who led the oldest guerrilla in the world, so he was asked to take away the card with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
But when he arrived with the investigation team at the location of the corpse, he did not recognize it by its physical appearance, because it was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a peasant of the area, without glasses and much leaner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Accompanied by a Galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a sampler and a lantern, Eliazar compared the fingerprints of the corpse with those of the card.
His eye did not deceive him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was the official who confirmed to Defense Minister Juan Carlos Pinzón that yes, he was the supreme leader of the FARC.
In search of the fingerprint
For a typist from Sijín de Cali the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos made to Eliazar González, in a press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
A lot of people don't know our work.
Fingerprinting is an exact science, with no margin for error, that can be crucial in solving crimes.
In addition to identifying corpses, typists support investigations for crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of those captured.
When captured, many offenders present false identification cards or have no documents.
We take their fingerprints and look for them in the database.
The researcher said that in one case of theft he had to remove part of the wall of a house, because in this place the thief had pressed his hand to bring out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not adequate surfaces to take a fingerprint, but in this case we were able to get the imprint of the whole hand and identify the offender who had participated in different robberies," he recalls.
Fingerprints can also rule out or confirm suspects in homicide cases.
Recently a dead man was found with bottles of drink around him.
Through the investigation it was determined that a relative may be a suspect in the crime and indeed a fingerprint on the bottle coincided.
Even if this does not guarantee that he is the murderer, it puts him at the scene of the crime.
A CTI typist explained that "fingerprints are extracted from objects with chemical or physical reagents".
When they appear, a sampler or tape is used to remove them.
Subsequently, the fingerprints are sent to Asif, the database of decliners, or to the National Civil Registry.
"The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians," said the ITC expert.
He explained that it's not all about how you show in the CSI TV program.
As not everything that glitters is gold, not everything you touch necessarily becomes a footprint.
It can, however, be used, if the necessary confrontation is carried out.
'Indignados' defy authorities in New York
Hundreds of demonstrators jostled in front of Zuccotti Square to camp.
Many of the people complied with the evacuation order and moved to a nearby park.
Supporters of the Occupy Wall Street movement defied New York authorities on Tuesday by trying to re-enter, thanks to a court order, the Manhattan square, from where they were evacuated at dawn and when they tried to occupy another park in the Big Apple.
Hundreds of protesters jostled in front of Zuccotti Square, where they wanted access thanks to a judicial order that allows the 'indignados' to camp again in this place, while the other part of the movement responded to the evacuation by occupying a park further north of the city, where there were new stops.
"Our idea is that if the court does not allow us to camp in the square again, we will move to another place and we will continue the legal struggle to return to Zuccotti, and through sit-ins and peaceful protests," said Mark Bray, a spokesman for the Occupy Wall Street movement.
Bray detailed that the response of the "indignados" to the evacuation of their camp personally dictated by New York Mayor Michael Bloomberg reached the courts, where Judge Lucy Billings issued an order that prohibited the forced evacuation of the place and allowed protesters to remain in the camp.
In addition, the 'indignados' occupied a new park located at the confluence of the Canal Street and Sixth Avenue generating stations, very close to the entrance to the Holland Tunnel, which unites New York and New Jersey, owned by Trinity Church Parish.
At least for an hour they managed to occupy the place, but then the police moved there and arrested some demonstrators, although Bray could not confirm the concrete figure, assuring Efe that he saw some journalists who had also been handcuffed.
The organization assures that there are centenarians of people who had settled in this place, where a delegation of religious leaders came in support of the members of the movement and tried to intervene on their behalf in front of the police.
Meanwhile, Zuccotti Square - which is a privately owned compound - remains closed pending the celebration of a judicial hearing scheduled for Tuesday during which the legality of this morning's evacuation must be analyzed.
Some protesters displaced until then carried and distributed copies of this judicial order at that time and they even delivered it to the agents guarding the square, which caused "some small clashes," said Bray, who denounced the fact that some officials beat the demonstrators.
The judiciary prohibits authorities from evacuating members of Occupy Wall Street or enforcing "laws issued after the occupation began or barring protesters from re-entering the park with tents or other properties they previously used."
Mayor Bloomberg told reporters that, because of this court order, the city had suspended the reopening of the space to the public and protesters, but warned them that local laws do not allow them to set up with tents and sleeping bags.
The city councillor personally defended the dawn evacuation in Zuccotti Square, an operation during which 200 people were arrested and which was decided because the demonstrators were "violating the law".
Bloomberg explained that he had given the order to evacuate the square because it became "a place where people did not come to protest, but to violate the laws and in some cases, to harm other people" because "some shops had received threats" and residents were afraid "for their quality of life".
"This morning's evacuation at dawn was repugnant and demonstrates that Bloomberg is basically more interested in defending the financial interests than those of American workers," added the spokesman of the movement, which accused the mayor of "not respecting freedom of expression".
Occupancy Wall Street officials also said they do not plan to hold "grand actions" for Thursday in collaboration with community organizations and unions to commemorate the two-month protests, which began on Sept. 17.
