Japan reborn after earthquake
GDP rises 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the downward spiral of early March
Since March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, still convalescent after the devastating earthquake that became a nuclear crisis, the worst disaster in the Japanese country since the Second World War.
Initial estimates by the Tokyo government put material losses at $300,000 million, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seems to have eased.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, the Gross Domestic Product data between July and September served to turn the page definitively: GDP rose by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% at an annualized rate.
The second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - also assumes the greatest pace of increase since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly explained by the resumption of equipment acquisitions to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and post-tsunami.
In fact, businesses increased their investment by 1.1%, compared with the 0.9% decline in capital spending observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of uninterrupted increases.
However, the real stimulus of the Japanese economy is not based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse that invites us to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - infrastructure, to use deficiencies to grow from scratch.
Japan has woken up mainly thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japan's GDP.
This variable rose a 1%, driven by higher spending on vehicles, travel and entertainment activities.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo returned to the domestic market when the yen - the Japanese currency - became one of the "safe havens" chosen by investors fleeing the eurozone debt crisis and the unrest forecasts of the United States, a privilege that weighs like a slab in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger divide, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic float line is determined by the health of major technology groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, blamed their weak results between July and September for the contribution of the yen.
While markets continue their siege in the peripheral countries of the EU, Yoshihiko Noda's government is not letting its guard down.
"We need to monitor the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen," Secretary of State for Economic Policy Motohisa Furukawa said yesterday.
And indeed, the outlook is not at all encouraging.
The Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) said the majority of member countries showed clearer signals of an economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates the inflection points of the global economy has highlighted that the main powers are being restricted.
Because it has decreased four decimal places to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 in August.
Eurozone was even below average, which is in the 100 level, falling eight decimal places to 99.13 points.
Athens fuels doubts again
Papadimos says adjustments will be approved, but conservatives won't sign any written commitments
With peripheral risk premiums triggered and uncertainty reinstalled in parks, Greece continues to become entangled in the labyrinth that leads to the exit from the great European debt crisis.
The feeling that the "consensus" of the new Greek Transitional Government is imposed rather by the demands of Brussels than by a real conviction of the political forces is beginning to be confirmed by the facts.
While the new Prime Minister, Lukas Papadimos, signalled yesterday that there is no alternative for structural reforms and that the period of one hundred days established in his appointment may be short to apply them, the leader of the conservative New Democracy party, Antonis Samaras, assured that he would not support the new austerity measures under any circumstances and reiterated his demand for new elections for the planned date,  that of 19 February.
"The main task of this Government is to implement the decisions of the summit of 26 October," Papadimos said when he opened a parliamentary debate yesterday that will end tomorrow with a vote of confidence in the new executive.
A package of 24 programmes to boost employment, the reform of the disciplinary code for civil servants and new measures against tax evasion will be the first initiatives.
However, Samaras' message casts doubt on his position: "We are committed to helping the Transitional Government, but we have not committed ourselves to anything more."
The conservative leader went a step further in his pulse than the EU and IMF, the bodies that must release the 8,000 million that Athens urgently needs, and made it clear that he will not approve any letter of commitment to carry out the adjustments.
But the European Commission, still irritated by the impact caused by the va-tout of Papandreu's referendum, reiterated yesterday that its demand is firm: it will not release the aid if the new government and the leaders of the main Greek parties do not sign "an unambiguous written commitment as soon as possible".
Economic Affairs spokesman Amadeu Altafaj said troika inspectors would return "very quickly" to Athens to discuss with the new government "the necessary elements to pay the sixth tranche" of 8,000 million, even if there is no definitive date either.
The Greeks still have a long way to go.
Queen Sofía: "They are instruments for progress and hope"
The Queen stresses Spain's "preponderant" place in this type of finance
Spain "has reached a leading place at the global level in the role of Micro-finance".
Queen Sofía recalled that the country has become in the last two decades the second donor on the planet with regard to this instrument of cooperation whose "essence" lies in the fact that it is an "instrument for social progress, justice and hope in a better future for all humanity, based on trust in the human being".
The Queen inaugurated yesterday the V-e World Microcredit Summit in Valladolid with the certainty that "there is no doubt" that this type of operation is "absolutely indispensable" to achieve the Millennium Development Goals established by the United Nations for 2015, and, "especially, in the one that aims to reduce to half the volume of people living on incomes below one dollar a day,  to which the "poverty line" is set.
Spain "continues to work" to expand the network of beneficiaries "in all corners of the planet, and assumes this task with "responsibility", said Queen Sofía, who hoped that the initiatives and contributions originated during the Summit, which will last until Thursday, "guarantee the creation of new capacities and better opportunities for the poorest and especially for women".  the main beneficiaries of these loans.
We have "achieved a lot of goals" and "we face a lot of challenges".
The Microcredit Summit is envisaged not only as a forum for debate, but also as the platform from which to promote "two basic goals".
Thus, Her Majesty explained that the target is that by the end of 2015 there will be 175 million poor families who have accessed these financial services and that one hundred million of these families will be lifted out of the poverty line in which they now live.
The impetus in the design of microcredits in Spain and the rest of the world "followed the path initiated a few years ago in a pioneering way" by Muhammad Yunus, Queen Sofía stressed as an "act of justice and due recognition".
And she described the father of this instrument as an "admirable idealist in the universal cause of the fight against poverty", whose work she has known since 15 years ago, when the Queen travelled to Bangladesh to learn on the ground about her lending policy.
