In this sense, she argued that it would be a mistake to vinculate cooperation with developing countries at times of economic prosperity, because it is a "permanent obligation".
Jimenez considered that microcredits presuppose "a serious and rigorous policy dedicated to the eradication of poverty", and now "more than ever" the governments of developed countries must work under criteria of solidarity and not allow it to be the victim of cuts.
For Spain, microcredit is "one of the main lines of development cooperation".
The Secretary of State for International Cooperation, Soraya Rodriguez, applauded "the success" of giving "confidence" to the "excluded people to whom all close the door"; and the mayor of Valladolid, Francisco Javier León de la Riva, welcomed those present in a city that "opens its doors contaminated with the spirit of solidarity".
The CDU proposes to elect the European President by universal suffrage
The first day of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU) congress on Monday 14 November in Leipzig took place without any real difficulty for Angela Merkel, Chancellor but also President of the Christian Democratic Party.
The future of Europe was not initially planned on the agenda but was imposed in the autumn, notably to satisfy activists who consider the government's policy too lax vis-à-vis the Greeks today and perhaps the Italians tomorrow.
The motion on the presidency of the European Commission, proposed by the management, was adopted almost unanimously.
Out of 1,001 delegates, only nine voted against and ten abstained.
The standing ovation of several minutes to which Angela Merkel was entitled, at the end of their speeches and, a few hours later, Wolfgang Schäuble, the very Europhile Minister of Finance, left no room for doubt.
The main idea of the Chancellor - and of the motion - can be summed up in a slogan: the answer to the crisis "is not less Europe but more Europe".
Not only because Europe is peace, but because 'nine million jobs depend directly on the euro'.
For the Chancellor, "the time has come for a breakthrough in Europe."
This could lead to changes to the Lisbon Treaty to strengthen the EU's control over the budgetary policies of the euro zone countries, but it could also lead to the election of the President of the European Commission by universal suffrage "in order to give Europe a face".
In any case, this is one of the proposals of the motion adopted by the congress whose inspiration is clearly Wolfgang Schäuble.
Admittedly, it is unlikely that the Twenty-Seven will quickly agree on this revolution: Britain is hostile to it and the leaders of the CDU believe that Nicolas Sarkozy is too.
