What is sick leave fraud?
After the benefits, the UMP and the government launched the offensive on sick leave.
Nicolas Sarkozy will be in Bordeaux on Tuesday 15 November to visit a family allowance fund, and give a speech on the theme - recurrent since 2007 - of the fight against social fraud and welfare.
And to accompany this offensive, which starts from a desire to make savings in a context of austerity, but is no less heralding an axis of the presidential campaign on the right, the majority wants to focus on sick leave.
Firstly with a view to budgetary savings: the government plans to impose on private sector employees a fourth day of waiting before taking charge of a work stoppage.
Clearly, without a specific company agreement, an employee who falls ill would lose four days' salary, so at least 15% of his monthly income.
A measure that is likely to arouse anger, but which would bring in 280 million euros, according to Les Echos.
And which would be accompanied by another measure, of more symbolic scope: imposing on civil servants a day of non-compensated waiting in the event of a work stoppage (they have so far no waiting period, against three days in the private sector).
While these issues are under discussion, the majority also raises the issue of fraud, this time targeting abuses related to work stoppages.
"The controls will be much more important and, in addition, if you are caught, you will refund," warned Xavier Bertrand at the microphone of RTL, Sunday, November 13.
As with other cases, the announcement effects seem somewhat disproportionate to the reality of work stoppage fraud.
Since 2002, it has been the subject of constant monitoring and political offensives, which have mostly borne fruit.
The French are no sicker than elsewhere in Europe.
Let us first focus on the national figures.
According to the National Health Insurance Fund (CNAM), more than €237 million in daily allowances were issued in 2006.
According to the Institute for Research and Documentation in Health Economics, daily allowances accounted for 5% of health expenditure in 2008, with 11.3 billion euros.
Of this amount, 46% concerned maternity leave and accidents at work, and 54% concerned sick leave, i.e. 6.2 billion euros.
And therefore 2.5% of health expenditure.
In 2010, the French experienced an average of 14.5 days off work, compared to 17.8 in 2009, according to a study by the Alma Consulting group.
Another survey, published in 2007 by the career management site Monster.com, showed that 75% of the 40,000 French employees surveyed said they had not taken any sick leave.
Another study, this time from the Health Insurance, specifies that in 2010, 37% of sick leave was for less than 8 days, 22% from 8 to 14 days, 15% from 15 days to one month, 15% from one to three months and 11% beyond.
When compared with their European neighbours, French employees are no more prone than elsewhere to work stoppages.
A long study conducted in 2010 by two CNRS researchers showed that between 1994 and 2001, the overall absence rate (for health reasons or not) fluctuated, in France, between 10% and 11%, against 20% and 28% in Denmark, 15% in the United Kingdom or 16% and 18% in the Netherlands.
Sick leave fraud represents very little compared to undeclared work.
As for fraud, it is only small.
The strengthening of legislation since 2002 means that checks are systematic on sick leave of more than 45 days.
In 2008, out of 1.5 million checks, the CNAM found that 13% of the 285,000 carried out for short-term stoppages were "unjustified or too long", i.e. 37,050 cases.
In the case of systematically controlled absences of more than 45 days, there were 11% of "unsuitable or unjustified" cases out of 1.2 million, or 132,000.
In total, 169,000 "unjustified" cases, out of several million employees who have had sick leave.
A figure that represents very little comparison, for example, to that of undeclared work.
According to UMP MP Dominique Tian, author of a report on the issue in June, it would represent 9 to 15 billion euros of tax shortfall per year, more than the total cost of daily allowances, and therefore infinitely more than fraud to the latter.
Papademos: Greece will have to implement a new adjustment plan
Greece will need a new adjustment programme to turn its economy around.
This was stated on Monday, November 14, by Prime Minister Lucas Papademos, before Parliament, adding that the hundred days given to his unity government would not be enough to accomplish this task.
"To continue the efforts to recover the economy, we need the support of our European partners and a new fiscal adjustment programme," said the head of government, who delivered his first public speech at the opening of the debate on the vote of confidence in Parliament on Wednesday.
