Legalize euthanasia and assisted suicide, says expert panel
Canadians live in denial of death, says Royal Society of Canada report
In palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions, and physicians to work together to ensure better palliative care beyond cancer.
Canadian society lives in denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians agree to speak with their doctor about the conditions in which they want to die and make arrangements to do so.
This is one of the conclusions of a massive report by the Royal Society of Canada, in which six experts related to various fields, including ethics, law and medicine, participated.
This committee recommends that the government amend the Criminal Code to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, where appropriate, for a patient deemed competent to make such a decision.
At the outset, experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
While Canada ranked 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has spawned a culture in which people are afraid to talk about death."
Medicalization or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, report experts commissioned by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the wish most Canadians have to die at home, 68.6% end up dying in hospital.
Overall, Quebec has the highest rate in Quebec, with 86% of deaths occurring in hospital.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that run counter to the position of the federal government, which has already said that it does not want to change anything in the Criminal Code regarding euthanasia and assisted suicide.
However, according to the experts, who also reviewed all countries where these approaches are legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that this decriminalization leads to abuses in the application, that is, the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide on incompetent or non-consenting people.
On the contrary, Jocelyn Downie, co-signatory of the report, said yesterday in a teleconference, we would find more cases of these excesses precisely in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
"Euthanasia is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal."
"Assisted suicide is practiced in Canada, where it is clearly illegal," says Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians in favour of euthanasia
Recall that 85% of Canadians have already voted in favor of euthanasia because they believe it would allow people at the end of life to alleviate their suffering, according to an Angus Reid poll conducted in 2010.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not send the message that the lives of the elderly or disabled are less valuable.
As for those who have practiced assisted suicide, 41% of respondents believe that they should not be prosecuted.
When it comes to maintaining or discontinuing care with a patient, the situation is less clear, say the report's authors.
Also, in the list of their recommendations, they suggest that it be stated in the Criminal Code that withdrawal of care for which there has been a legally valid refusal is not criminal.
The expert committee also asks that health professionals be trained in the duty to respect a refusal of end-of-life care, without fear of criminal prosecution.
In palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions, and physicians to work together to ensure better palliative care beyond cancer.
Finally, with regard to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the Committee requests that it be considered, when it is not used to reduce physical pain, as euthanasia, and that it be subject to the same procedures.
Reservations from other experts
Some experts in the field of health law have already expressed reservations about the findings of the Royal Society of Canada's expert report.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, described as "extreme" the position of the experts who signed the report, among other things because it does not limit the practice of euthanasia to the terminally ill.
"This opens the door to a situation where anyone who is tired of life and who is over 18 years old could ask for assistance in committing suicide," said Deschamps, who had consulted a summary of the report yesterday.
Mr. Deschamps also points out that the authors of the report seem to place the autonomy of the person above all the other values that participate in the social fabric of society.
However, "in society," he says, "there are guidelines and constraints."
Health law expert Margaret Somerville also expressed "strong opposition" to the report's findings, calling it a "pro-euthanasia manifesto."
Margaret Somerville, who is herself a Fellow of the Royal Society of Canada, particularly disputes the report's data on the absence of abuse in some countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legalized, namely the Netherlands and Oregon.
