Austria's ruling Social Democrat/Christian Democrat grand coalition government decided on Tuesday to enshrine in the constitution a budgetary "golden rule" in order to reduce public deficits and thus avoid a possible downgrading by rating agencies of Austria's sovereign rating (triple A).
It was Social Democrat Chancellor Werner Faymann who himself announced this decision at the end of a Council of Ministers, whilst the Austrian public debt is 74.6%, well above the maximum 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty, but well below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece and Spain.
