Energy policy:
Facts must prevail over dogmas
If there is one subject that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or under the influence of emotion, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity have a direct impact on the purchasing power and competitiveness of enterprises.
It is healthy that an election meeting is an opportunity to reflect on such issues and the place that nuclear power plays in them.
The debate will only be fruitful if it explores all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
While we are 7 billion human beings on the planet, demographic change will lead to a doubling of the demand for electricity by 2050, unless we deprive a huge part of the world's population of a vital element.
At the same time, it will be necessary to compensate for the scarcity of fossil resources to continue to produce electricity permanently, without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to fight against climate change, a subject that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains isolated in its decision to abandon nuclear power.
This is not the case for Belgium, which subjects its own to the need to be able to find an alternative source capable of substituting itself, nor for Switzerland, which just intends to build only the latest generation power stations.
Conversely, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to name but a few, are pursuing their projects with determination.
The United States, for its part, decided after Fukushima to add a unit to its fleet by resuming the construction of a plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, focused on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, reality contradicts the discourse.
The choice of Berlin will result in higher electricity prices, energy dependence aggravated by the increased use of imported gas, particularly from Russia, and a jump in CO2 emissions driven by the construction of gas and coal power plants.
In a few months, all these unfortunate effects are already being felt.
The case of Denmark is worth pondering.
European champion of wind power, from which it derives 30% of its electricity, it is also one of the largest users of coal and gas because of the intermittency of the wind; as a result, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
Conversely, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay an electricity bill 40% higher than that of French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy is a key factor of competitiveness and a guarantee of maintaining the industrial base on the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear power would lead to a sharp increase in the price of electricity, which would make illusory the fine declarations on the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power.
A price that a large majority of French people refuse to pay, especially since they do not show opposition in principle to this energy, polls show.
Let us remember that our country's energy policy has made it possible to build an industrial sector of 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 induced jobs.
Strongly exporting, it leads to a galaxy of SMEs specialized in international markets and makes them very creators of jobs that cannot be relocated.
If the France were to decide to phase out nuclear power, it would be sacrificing many of these SMEs by reducing the 6 billion euros of French exports of nuclear equipment and services annually.
What electrician would order an EPR designed to operate for sixty years while the decline of its manufacturer would be programmed?
To solve the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no miracle source of electricity production, any more than there is a diabolical one.
Areva's development of low-CO2 emitting, nuclear and renewable solutions testifies to the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear power, maintaining the highest level of safety is an absolute imperative.
We France have a Safety Authority that exercises uncompromising and transparent control over existing power plants such as the Flamanville site.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, are inhabited by the same obsession with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, intervened under normal operating conditions; It has remained without human or environmental consequences.
At Chernobyl, the design of the reactor and unforgivable human faults caused the tragedy.
In Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident is the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude that caused the death of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it did for the previous two.
The result of this approach and cooperation between French and German safety authorities, operators and manufacturers, the EPR has a design that makes it capable of withstanding such phenomena.
While it is considered by all electricians wishing to build a power plant, stopping its construction in Flamanville would be a magnificent gift offered to the competitors of Areva and EDF by leaving them the way free to seize leadership in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy mix for our country, but it would be irresponsible to allow emotion, dogmas and partisan manoeuvres to dominate such a decisive debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy pursued under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticised from various angles - the congestion of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of figures, compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "country of human rights" of the France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has made the news, the Minister of the Interior (see Liberation of May 23) proclaiming in passing that the France "does not need foreign talent, masons and restaurant waiters".
But it is rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
It is that there is a fairly broad consensus on this subject between left and right.
On the right, the tone was set by Jacques Chirac who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country with nearly 2 million immigrant workers", and on the left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot accommodate all the misery in the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, fear of the invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared on both the left and the right.
For both sides, immigrants are perceived as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that will be deigned to be given to immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande confines himself to banalities, indicating that co-development will solve our "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may pay off electorally; but it is economically very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent book summarizing the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among scholars on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth.  wages and employment in immigrant-receiving countries.
Restricting immigration anemies growth and hurts jobs.
Fears about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they may substitute for national workers, especially the low-skilled, exerting downward pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, working mainly in sectors with a shortage of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract domestic employees, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors in which training does not follow the supply of jobs.
A positive effect on wages
In the same way that a surgeon will find it difficult to work in a country with a shortage of anaesthetists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants mean that immigrant arrivals have a positive effect on the wages and employment of nationals.
Giovanni Peri has calculated that a 1% increase in migration flows leads to an increase of between 0.6 and 0.9% in real wages in the long term.
This is without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among American Nobel Prize winners; Google, Intel, PayPal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, on average up to 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization, for example, estimates that, in Germany, an immigrant arriving at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (revenue minus expenditure) of €150,000 to public budgets on average over his or her lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the beginning of his mandate, to get the missing growth points "with his teeth".
The teeth in question, by serving to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, it remains to think about European democracy
Democracy is a precious commodity; It is also a fragile asset.
The European continent should be able to remember this which, having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, experienced throughout the twentieth century the tragedies of the Great War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the Gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that it would suffice, for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, to exercise the vote, and to exercise it in the most direct way possible.
We know, since Napoleon "the Little", that this was a facility of thought.
Universal suffrage, to be the necessary condition of democracy, is not the sufficient condition and can even become an "instrument of oppression" as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, organization, separation and control of powers, education, Enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis of Europe that we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is just as much and first and foremost a crisis of politics and democracy.
The palinody of the true-false Greek referendum will have had in this respect the value of a double revealer: that of the need for a powerful return of politics, but also that of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be thought to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle have now shifted, and for many of them, the Republican soldiers are no longer firing in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain by demanding a succession of national referendums, organised according to necessity and in a dispersed order.
A blank cheque to the absolute European monarch or a leap with both feet into the void of nationalist withdrawal: what a choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want cleavers, but a common, rightful, serene and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain or Portugal - and we would no longer know where to stop the list - because there is only one crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is Europe as a whole that bows to the dictates of the markets and rating agencies, which suffers from its impotence and lack of solidarity.
The whole of Europe is being humiliated on the international stage.
There is concern about transfers of sovereignty to Europe - but it is Europe as a whole that is slowly losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The urgency is to give back to popular sovereignty the steering of the European project.
Because it is together that Europeans will be able to reduce their debt burden, free themselves from markets and prepare for the future by investing.
The way out of the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, except, of course, that we lead to disaster.
After having fought for a long time against this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for European economic government.
Either.
But to think so without stronger political and democratic integration, and experienced as such by citizens, would be a new folly and a new dead end.
We must take on a new stage in the construction of Europe.
To make the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" republicans.
The Revolution in interests could not suffice.
This lesson remains valid.
We need to build a more economically integrated Europe.
This can only be achieved by building a more politically democratic Europe, a genuine European popular sovereignty.
To make Europe, let us make Europeans.
