Terrorist axis
The analysis of the calls made directs to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two numbers are of particular interest to investigators: one leads to a Nigerien who has spent a long time in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the birthplace of Boko Haram, and the other to a man who says he is close to AQIM and the sect.
"This is a step forward, but we should probably wait for more formal evidence before talking about operational cooperation between AQIM and Boko Haram."
"But it's possible."
"We have known for years that the sect has external financial and intellectual support and that it is increasingly active," said Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, this "support" had been increasingly evident in the evolution and discourse of Boko Haram or in its modus operandi, which now involve the use of suicide bombers or explosive devices increasingly complex and of the same quality as those used by AQIM.
The international community, starting with Washington, has therefore put pressure on Abuja to take into account the problems posed by Boko Haram.
Nigerian authorities have long regarded the group as a community of illumined people who are not worthy of interest.
Quick success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram - which means in Hausa "Western education is a sin" - advocates the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the association is a quick success.
It is becoming politicized and demanding strict adherence to Sharia law while its activists engage in the fight against the godless central government.
The latter primarily target churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants were particularly active, increasing attacks on police stations.
Abuja's reaction is, as usual, without nuance.
The army invests the city, there are 800 dead.
Mohammed Yusuf was arrested alive and killed in prison.
From then on, the sect became radicalized and left its fiefdoms in the north.
Last Christmas, it claimed responsibility for an attack that killed 80 people in Jos, then another in Abuja.
In June, Boko Haram attacked the secure police headquarters in Abuja in a suicide attack, its first.
In August, the local headquarters of the United Nations will be its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa that would sail from Mauritania to Somalia via Nigeria is now worrying all security specialists.
While AQIM has invested Mali and Niger, and al-Shabaab's Somalis operate in Kenya, Boko Haram is emerging as a new threat in the heart of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned against Boko Haram and said he was ready "to share all intelligence".
The world according to Republican presidential candidates
On China, on Iran, on aid to Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, and Rick Perry compete in simplism and ignorance.
Can an America weakened by the crisis manage a complex world with simple, even simplistic ideas?
Listening to Republican presidential candidates, voters might believe it.
In recent days, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, Rick Perry and others have multiplied thunderous statements and shortcuts in foreign policy, traditionally a Republican strong point.
On China, on Iran, on aid to Israel, slogans - often unsubstantiated - are rife.
Mitt Romney, the best placed in the race for the nomination of the "Grand Old Party", threatened to drag the Chinese before the WTO and to blame them "for manipulation of their currency", a theme carried by an America exasperated by the migration of whole swathes of its industry to Asia.
Too bad if it is to involve triggering a trade war, he said.
Jon Huntsman, Obama's former ambassador to China and the only candidate with a sophisticated foreign policy vision, nearly choked up on an attitude that "flatters" emotions.
He called for a robust but constructive dialogue with Beijing (Obama's current position).
But Huntsman, who is stagnating in the depths of the polls, remains inaudible.
Like Reagan
Romney also promised military strikes on Iran if sanctions fail to halt its nuclear program.
"If I am elected, I will stop Iran," he boasted.
"If Obama is re-elected, they will have the bomb."
He also promised to increase military aid to Israel, accusing Obama of failing the partner.
The entrepreneur Herman Cain, the second best placed candidate, displays an embarrassing ignorance of the files.
Recently, he called for countering the Chinese military threat because Beijing is "trying to develop a nuclear capability" – apparently ignoring the fact that China has held the military atom since 1964!
Texas Governor Rick Perry, who supports Israel and wants strikes against Iran, says he is ready to engage the US military in Mexico against drug cartels.
The use of torture against suspected terrorists, banned by Obama in 2009, is also advocated by Cain, Perry and candidate Michele Bachmann.
This is a far cry from the 2008 Republican candidate, John McCain, a foreign policy heavyweight.
The current president's opponents counter that Reagan also had simple ideas and that he won the Cold War.
They recall that Obama himself was an amateur and that he had to put water in his wine when it comes to counterterrorism.
They rightly insist on the failure of his naive dialogue with Iran, on the too hasty departure of the "boys" from Iraq, on his prevarications in Libya, thus sticking a label of weakness.
But the attack is not so easy.
The public views Obama's national security record, which eliminated bin Laden, rather positively.
Since Iraq, it has been wary of military interventions that lead to stalemate.
And, by arguing that America must be economically rebuilt to resurrect its leadership, Obama strikes more just.
Nord Stream, the new gateway for Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, directly linking Western Europe to Russia at the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered service.
It must supply gas for the equivalent of 30 million homes.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with a bang.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part, last Tuesday, on the shores of the Baltic, between orchestra and fine buffet, in the inauguration of Nord Stream, this new gas pipeline that connects Russia directly to Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte turned together the steering wheel of the valve controlling the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive in Western Europe each year through a first 1,224 km tube linking the St. Petersburg region to the state of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube is to be completed at the end of 2012, making it possible to deliver a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, equivalent to all French consumption.
And there is already talk of the possibility of building a third one on the same course.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project looks like a victory.
The project was strongly opposed by Poland and the Baltic countries.
Nord Stream will make it possible to deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding any overland passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries lose some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to influence Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
This means that the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But this is at the cost of weakening the Europe of energy, since the project has created a breach between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has been able to triumph its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which consume a lot of gas and whose deposits are declining.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically," confirmed François Fillon in inaugurating this pipeline, demonstrating how major gas contracts are as political as economic.
All this explains the broad smiles displayed by the leaders of Gazprom, present in large numbers in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater tube is made of concrete-sheathed steel to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at an average of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from the Second World War.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed as a precaution," says Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to multiply measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, as heavy as 242 Eiffel Towers, that nothing interrupts along its entire length: no valve, no maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project abandoned it while the Swedes were reluctant to see a Russian state-owned company permanently established off their coast.
"In the event of damage, we stop the gas flow in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who have planned the welds to experience a leak every 100,000 years.
The condition of the pipeline is monitored by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, for external observation, as well as by a device that circulates inside the pipeline.
In the shape of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, one meter wide in diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
On arrival, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 meters second, it delivers precise information on the possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo any repairs.
The flow of gas is simply ensured by pressure.
It is 200 bars at the start, and 100 at the arrival.
Five companies joined forces to make this project a reality.
The leader remains Gazprom, which retains 51% of the shares.
It was joined by Germany's E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies set up a joint venture, Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to this company, for twenty years renewable, all the gas transmission capacity.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of how much gas is actually transported," Müller said.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline was provided 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach €7.4 billion for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to pay for themselves, since only Gazprom bears the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic at Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the exit door of the gas.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specifics of incoming gas before it is transferred to German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a brand book.
Created fifteen years ago by an Italian company, the Moleskine wants to restore the taste of writing.
It has a scent of adventure, of hours spent writing by candlelight.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, elastic, off-white leaves, as if aged by time.
However, the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a design but distinguished notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, was in charge of launching the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an ancient production technique, the mole skin (mole skin) which refers to a varnished cotton used to cover benches for example.
This type of notebook was very popular with writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has revived an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of avant-garde artists, until the twentieth century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the head of the brand at Modo Modo.
The success is there.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million pieces sold.
This is a far cry from the confidential production of the early years, when only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond Italy's borders and is exported to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to establish a robotic portrait of the buyer, because the notebook seduces the businessman as well as the student and the professionals.
Like Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The small Italian company, which started with 12 employees, now has almost 100 employees and has had two offices since 2008; one in Milan and the other in New York.
It distributes its notebooks in bookstores, from Fnac to small shops in the city center and has been able to impose its identity.
"We have kept pace with the times and this new need for writing, despite the rise of e-mails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand launched an exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, she also launched a leopard blanket at the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has diversified its products: bags, diary, pens, computer cases... The brand is available on a whole range of supports.
In autumn 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskine's history.
Why does the unemployment rate for disabled workers remain so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th Disability Employment Week opens today.
Despite a proactive public policy implemented in 2005, the unemployment rate for people with disabilities is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared to 9% for the population as a whole.
Discouraging?
"No," says Éric Blanchet, executive director of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled. "
"The progress made over the past fifteen years has been considerable."
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher."
"However, much remains to be done."
It must be said that for the unemployed with disabilities, there are still many obstacles before accessing employment.
They are rather old: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have the baccalaureate and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared with an average of 38%.
In short, so many criteria that singularly complicate the return to employment, and which "constitute the crux of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, director general of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
So much for the objective brakes.
There remains the unspoken, the mentalities that evolve, certainly, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité indicated that the managers interviewed have "a low level of knowledge of disability", with an "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, psychically or intellectually deficient".
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, set in a law of... 1987.
The latest available figures, from 2008, show a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, director general of Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The proof: the number of "taxed" establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
" But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, especially in large groups. "
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of companies with 100 to 199 employees.
Hazard: "What happiness"
Before facing the Blues on Tuesday night (20:45) Eden Hazard and Georges Leekens did not hide the pleasure that gives them this friendly match.
We will not go so far as to write that there was connivance between them, but the image is symbolic.
Sitting side by side on the stage of the auditorium of the Stade de France, Georges Leekens and Eden Hazard have indeed made peace.
Five months after his striker's moody gesture against Turkey, the Belgian coach has nothing but praise for him.
"I'm very happy with Eden, his progress and the fact that he's Belgian."
"I want to move forward," says the Lillois.
As for the contrast between his performances in club and selection, "it's a whole, he justified."
"In Lille, I'm there all year, which is not the case with Belgium."
"I have to get my bearings."
Spared against Romania on Friday night for this match against France, Hazard comes to Saint-Denis to finally "shine".
Without omitting the notion of "pleasure".
The Blues, he has encouraged them since the age of 7 and the victorious campaigns of 1998 and 2000.
"I've always been a supporter," he says.
Inevitably, this contributes to further strengthening the "special" character of this meeting.
Especially since opposite, "there is Mathieu (Debuchy), Yohan (Cabaye) and Adil (Rami)", he recalls.
"We crossed paths just now."
"Being able to play against them is nothing but happiness!"
Leekens, for his part, spoke of "pride".
"Pride" to play "a gala match".
"Proud" also to note - as a "neighbor" - that the France has "become a very high level team" a little more than a year after the trauma of Knysna.
"Laurent Blanc did a great job," he enthused.
While Belgium will miss the next Euro, the technician would see himself sharing the plane with the Blues direction... Brazil in 2014.
"Our little Belgians are getting big," he said.
"We're building something, the players are ambitious, they're hungry."
"You'll find out in the next games." The one against France included.
Portugal very confident
Paulo Bento's Portugal begins with great optimism its return play-off against Bosnia (22:00), this Tuesday in Lisbon.
In the first leg, both teams lacked realism.
"At the end of these 90 minutes, we will be a happy team and, above all, a happy country."
Paulo Bento can already see himself there, in Poland and Ukraine.
For him, there is no shadow of a doubt, the Selecçao, of which he has been at the helm since September 2010, will qualify for Euro 2012.
Portugal is actually only 90 minutes away from happiness.
But there is a game to play, and an opponent, Bosnia, to debunk.
In view of the first leg (0-0), Friday in the hell of Zenica, it seems obvious that the games are not done.
Portugal dominated the game for more than an hour, certainly, but they were unable to score that precious goal, which would have relieved them.
"It's a good result, but it carries a certain risk because we didn't score an away goal."
But at home, in their bright Stade de la Luz in Lisbon, the Portuguese are convinced to pass, in front of an audience that should be there as boiling, even if the game obviously promises to be "very tight", dixit an optimistic but lucid Bento.
"We are expecting a very close game, but we are quite confident that we can get the upper hand," said the 42-year-old Portuguese coach.
"We continue to have a 50% chance of being at Euro 2012," said Carlos Queiroz's successor.
Friday's draw from Bosnia forced the Portuguese to score and win.
A draw can be enough for the Bosnians, who also need to score.
"It's a good result, but it carries a certain risk because we didn't score an away goal," Bento said.
"We will play against a team that has a lot of technical qualities and has players with a lot of individual qualities," he added.
As in Zenica, the Portuguese will intend to put maximum pressure on the Bosnians from the outset so as not to "give them time to think."
A good idea, provided you are realistic this time.
